Definition

Hashing converts data into a fixed-length value using a one-way function.

One-way â†’ cannot be reversed

Same input â†’ same output

Small change â†’ completely different output

ğŸ”¹ Example
password = "secret123"
hash(password) = "5f4dcc3b5aa765d61d8327deb882cf99"


You cannot get secret123 back from the hash.

ğŸ”¹ Where hashing is used

Password storage

Data integrity checks

Digital signatures

ğŸ”¹ Rails example (Devise)
has_secure_password


or in Devise:

Password is hashed (bcrypt)

Only hash is stored in DB

Login = hash(input password) + compare

2ï¸âƒ£ Encryption
ğŸ”¹ Definition

Encryption converts data into unreadable form that can be reversed using a key.

Two-way process

Requires a key

Can decrypt back to original data

ğŸ”¹ Example
"credit_card" â†’ encrypt(key) â†’ "A9x#K!2"
"A9x#K!2" â†’ decrypt(key) â†’ "credit_card"

ğŸ”¹ Where encryption is used

Credit card numbers

Tokens

Sensitive personal data

Secure communication (HTTPS)

3ï¸âƒ£ Key Differences (Very Important)
Feature	Hashing	Encryption
Reversible	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
Key required	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
Purpose	Verify data	Protect data
Output length	Fixed	Variable
Password storage	âœ… Correct	âŒ Wrong
4ï¸âƒ£ Why passwords are hashed, not encrypted

If passwords were encrypted:

Server could decrypt them

Data breach â†’ passwords exposed

With hashing:

Server never knows the password

Only compares hashes

ğŸ‘‰ This is critical for security

5ï¸âƒ£ Salt & Pepper (Interview bonus)
ğŸ”¹ Salt

Random value added to password before hashing

Prevents rainbow table attacks

hash(password + salt)


Devise uses bcrypt, which includes salt internally.

ğŸ”¹ Pepper

Secret value stored in app config

Adds extra security

6ï¸âƒ£ One-line Interview Answers
Hashing

Hashing is a one-way function used to verify data, commonly for password storage.

Encryption

Encryption is a reversible process used to protect sensitive data that must be read later.

7ï¸âƒ£ Common Interview Trap

âŒ â€œPasswords are encrypted in databaseâ€
